Object.Field: Configuration #2 - IKM Oracle Partition Exchange Load - Synchronous - Flow Control - Without Validation

This package uses the scenarios of the mapping called "Configuration #2 - IKM Oracle Partition Exchange Load - Flow Control - Disable Constraints - Without Validation" to perform a full load of the partitioned table.
The scenarios in this package use Oracle Partition Exchange to perform the full load of the partitioned table with the IKM Oracle Partition Exchange Load.
This package performs the partition exchange operation without validation; thus, it is expected that source data belongs to the partition.
Flow control (CKM Oracle) is used to validate the source data before the exchange operation.
The first scenario changes the statistics preference of the table to incremental, and table constraints are disabled.
The next set of partitions is loaded synchronously, sequentially.
Local indexes are rebuilt after every partition exchange (in all 3 scenarios: first, next, and last).
The last scenario rebuilds global and local indexes, enables constraints, and gathers incremental stats.
This strategy offers the best combination of parameters, great performance and it ensures that data is validated (CKM Oracle) before the exchange operation. Here are some of the benefits:
1. Bad data is moved into the error tables before the exchange operation (flow control with CKM Oracle). 2. Table constraints of the partitioned table are disabled during the entire upload operation; thus the exchange operation is faster. 3. Local indexes are rebuilt after every partition exchange load. 4. Global indexes are rebuilt only once, after the last partition exchange operation. This may be faster than updating global indexes on every exchange operation. 5. Incremental statistics are gathered after the last partition exchange load operation.
Disadvantages: 1. Flow control takes time. The CKM Oracle knowledge module takes time to validate the source data. 2. The partitions are uploaded sequentially (see NOTE below), increasing the overall time it takes to perform the full upload operation of the partitioned table.
The package waits 5 seconds before launching the next partition upload. This is to ensure that the PARTITION_MONTH variable gets refreshed accordingly before assigning its value to the next scenario.
NOTE: The load is done in synchronous mode (sequentially). This is due to a limitation in the CKM Oracle. The CKM Oracle does not create UNQUE AK indexes for each flow table that is created by each scenario; thus, flow tables without indexes will perform poorly. To avoid performance problems, the scenarios are being executed in synchronous mode. The CKM Oracle index limitation will be fixed in future versions of ODI.
